body:
## Problem

On Windows, dotter always takes the `.sh` hook file, renders it via Handlebars, then forces `set_extension("bat")` to rename the cache output to `.bat`, and executes it with `cmd.exe`. This means the rendered `.sh` content (bash syntax) is fed to `cmd.exe`, which fails on every line:

```
'#!' is not recognized as an internal or external command.
'#' is not recognized as an internal or external command.
-n was unexpected at this time.
```

This happens even when a `.bat` version of the hook already exists in `.dotter/`. The current code in `hooks.rs`:

```rust
let mut script_file = cache_dir.join(location);
if cfg!(windows) {
    script_file.set_extension("bat");
}
```

always renames whatever the input file is — there is no platform-aware fallback to an existing `.bat` sibling.

Since the default hook path is `.dotter/pre_deploy.sh` (hardcoded in `args.rs`), there is no way to avoid this on Windows without passing `--pre-deploy .dotter/pre_deploy.bat` on every single `dotter deploy` invocation.

## Proposed Solution

On Windows, when the hook path points to a `.sh` file, check if a `.bat` sibling exists at the same location. If it does, use the `.bat` file instead:

```rust
let hook_location = location;
if cfg!(windows) && location.extension().map_or(false, |e| e == "sh") {
    let bat_sibling = location.with_extension("bat");
    if bat_sibling.exists() {
        hook_location = bat_sibling.as_path();
    }
}
```

This lets cross-platform dotfile repos ship both `pre_deploy.sh` (for Unix) and `pre_deploy.bat` (for Windows), and dotter picks the right one automatically — no `--pre-deploy` CLI overrides needed on every deploy.

## Alternatives Considered

- Using `--pre-deploy .dotter/pre_deploy.bat` on every deploy: works but requires remembering the flag or wrapping dotter in a script.
- Writing hooks in a cross-platform language (Python): requires a separate runner and does not fix the core issue that `.sh` files are force-converted to `.bat` syntax.
- Using Handlebars conditionals (`{{#if dotter.windows}}`) inside `.sh` hooks to emit `.bat` syntax on Windows: works for simple cases but is fragile and hard to maintain for complex multi-line scripts.

## Summary

Add support for [TOML 1.1](https://toml.io/en/v1.1.0), in particular, the ability to have newlines in inline tables:

```toml
name = { first = "Tom", last = "Preston-Werner" }
point = {x=1, y=2}
animal = { type.name = "pug" }
contact = {
    personal = {
        name = "Donald Duck",
        email = "donald@duckburg.com",
    },
    work = {
        name = "Coin cleaner",
        email = "donald@ScroogeCorp.com",
    },
}
```

## Background

TOML 1.1 was released in December 2025, and while most changes are relatively minor, it added the ability to insert newlines within inline tables `{...}`. This can make formatting _significantly_ nicer.

It should be straightforward to add support within dotter as the `toml` crate already supports the standard starting from v1
